Nehawu members say they too will strike after SARS made a final offer of a zero-percent increase. The union - which represents 45 percent of the workers - is threatening to bring SARS operations to a standstill. Nehawu General-Secretary Zola Saphtha has more. #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - A second union plans to down tools at the South African Revenue Service (SARS) over wages. The Public Servants' Association issued its intention to strike last week after a deadlock in wage discussions. Now Nehawu members say they too will strike after SARS made a final offer of a zero-percent increase. WATCH: Sars wage crisis | Employees to strike over 0% increase Both unions are demanding increases of up to 13 percent, citing rising food and fuel prices. Nehawu -- which represents 45 percent of the workers -- is threatening to bring SARS operations to a standstill. The revenue service chose not to respond to the latest strike announcement. A SARS official told eNCA that it will respond after another round of talks with Nehawu on Wednesday.